data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

In .NET 10, the Cosmos DB provider blocked sync operations by default but allowed you to opt back in (via `EnableSyncOverAsync`). **In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.** All your synchronous LINQ calls — `ToList()`, `First()`, `Count()`, and `SaveChanges()` — will throw `InvalidOperationException` at runtime with no workaround.

### The fix: convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
- Return types become `Task<T>` / `Task`
- Methods marked `async`, suffixed with `Async`
- LINQ terminals → async variants (`ToListAsync`, `FirstAsync`, `CountAsync`)
- `SaveChanges()` → `SaveChangesAsync()`

This will cascade — all callers up the chain (controllers, services) must also become `async`/`await`. Start from the lowest layer (repositories) and work upward.
